"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47916","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-04-28","<p> </p><p>There is no hard evidence that retaliatory eviction is a widespread problem in the private rented sector and the English Housing Survey shows that only 9% of tenancies are ended by the landlord. However, we are aware that this is an issue for some people. We recently published a discussion document on property conditions which invited views on whether restrictions should be placed on issue of possession notices where a tenant has requested a repair. The closing date for replies was 28 March and we are now considering the responses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47916/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47916/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent research his Department has undertaken on retaliatory evictions in the private rented sector.","false","Biography information for Mr Mike Thornton","Eastleigh","Mr Michael Thornton","196063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47917","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-01","<p> </p><p>Planning is a quasi-judicial process; it is a long-standing feature of the planning system that there is a right of appeal, just as there are with other local quasi-judicial decisions such as on licensing applications, gambling applications or parking fines.</p><p>The Localism Act 2011 has strengthened the role of Local Plans and abolished the last Administration's top-down Regional Strategies. Our streamlined National Planning Policy Framework strongly encourages areas to get up-to-date Local Plans in place, and we have been actively supporting councils in doing so. Local Plans now set the framework in which decisions on particular applications are taken, whether locally or at appeal, unless material considerations indicate otherwise.</p><p>Once adopted a neighbourhood plan will also become part of the area's statutory development plan – an example of this Government's localist agenda. Both local and neighbourhood plans are founded on thorough community involvement and are subject to public examination and consultation. Almost 1,000 communities have applied for a neighbourhood planning area to be designated, with 850 areas now designated.</p><p>Planning inspectors will take full account of all the evidence that is before them, including representations made by local residents and other interested parties. Each representation should be considered on their merits, paying careful regard to the relevant policy and material planning considerations.</p><p>Since the National Planning Policy Framework was introduced, the number of appeals received has fallen as has the number allowed. The quality of local decisions also remains high – 99 per cent of decisions are made locally with only approximately 1 per cent of planning applications overturned on appeal. Housing starts and housing construction are also up, as are permissions for new homes. This means there is more local decision-making, and our reforms are supporting badly-needed new homes within a locally-led planning system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-05-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47917/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47917/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that the wishes of the local people and decisions of the local council are given priority in appeal decisions by the Planning Inspectorate.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","196030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47918","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-04-28","<p> </p><p>A decision will be taken on the appeal against the establishment of the Sparkbrook and Springfield Business Improvement District in due course and all interested parties will be informed.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47918/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47918/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 13 February 2014, Official Report, column 800W, on Business Improvement Districts: Birmingham, when he expects to publish the report on the Business Improvement District for Sparkbrook and Springfield, or to reach a decision on that matter.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","196137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47919","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-04-28","<p>The Government has committed £780million to help deliver superfast broadband to 95 per cent of UK premises by 2017. We do not have data on the specific number of schools that would benefit from the programme. Public sector broadband requirements would be the managed by the department or local authority with responsibility for delivering the relevant policy.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47919/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47919/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many schools will benefit from his broadband rollout for schools.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","196097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47922","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-04-28","<p>The Government considers a wide range of available research when formulating gambling policy. The Government is mindful of the provenance of research, and its funding source, when interpreting findings.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47922/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47922/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, which research studies used by his Department in formulating policy on fixed odds betting terminals (a) have and (b) have not received industry funding or support; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","196046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47923","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-04-28","<p>I meet with a number of stakeholders to discuss their concerns. These stakeholders include problem gambling charities, faith groups and the Gambling Commission. The Government also received a number of representations from the charity sector to its 2013 consultation on the Triennial Review of Gaming Machine Stake and Prize Limits.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47923/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47923/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what representations he has received from the charity sector about the effect of gambling addiction; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","196003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47925","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-04-28","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not report the costs of recruitment marketing separately. The costs detailed in the following table show the total cost of regular recruiting by Service and include manpower costs; marketing campaigns (specific advertising); marketing operations (provision of the recruiting process i.e. call centres and website maintenance), and contract costs (i.e. medical and fitness testing).It should be noted that despite the redundancy notice, the Armed Forces are required to constantly recruit every year to maintain the levels of young personnel entering the three services.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Royal Navy</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Army</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Royal Air Force</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>TOTAL </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£33.2million</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£122.8million</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£35.4million</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£191.4million</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47925/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47925/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department spent on (a) armed forces recruitment and (b) armed forces recruitment marketing in 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Naomi Long","Belfast East","Naomi Long","196069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47926","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-04-29","<p>All armoured fighting vehicles deployed to Afghanistan will be returned to the UK. None of these have been destroyed and none are currently due to be sold.</p><p> </p><p>The information on costs associated with this activity cannot be readily broken out from the wider costs of all equipment and personnel recovery.</p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-04-29T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47926/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47926/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the number of armoured fighting vehicles which will be (a) returned to the UK, (d) destroyed or (c) sold by the time of the main withdrawal from Afghanistan; and what the costs associated with each of those categories are to date.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","196076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47927","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-04-28","<p>The Secretary of State discusses a range of topics with his counterparts from the Permanent Members of the UN Security Council, including subjects related to the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty. However, engagement with our international partners on this Treaty is led by the Foreign Secretary.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47927/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47927/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he last discussed the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty with his counterparts from the Permanent Members of the UN Security Council; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","196027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47928","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-04-28","<p>The Apache helicopter was taking part in a biannual joint multi national exercise and was travelling from West Freugh to Kinloss when the crew were given a warning notice. They followed correct flight procedures and safely conducted an emergency landing.</p><p> </p><p>An engineering fault investigation report identified a failure with the oil pump and the engine is now being replaced before further engineering checks are conducted and the aircraft is cleared to fly.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47928/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47928/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for what reason an Apache helicopter had to make an emergency landing outside Aberdeen during Exercise Joint Warrior.","false","Biography information for Angus Robertson","Moray","Angus Robertson","196036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47929","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-05-07","<p>A table that provides the data requested is attached.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47929/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47929/answer","20140416-PQ-02988B-Robertson-manpower-table-FINAL.XLS","20140416-PQ-02988B-Robertson-manpower-table-FINAL.XLS","Manpower","Manpower","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47929/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47929/answer/previousversion/8281","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many suitably qualified and experienced RAF personnel his Department has required for aircraft maintenance in each location in each of the last three years; and how many such posts were vacant in each location in each such year.","false","Biography information for Angus Robertson","Moray","Angus Robertson","196037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47931","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-04-28","<p>A definitive central list of those Service personnel who lost their lives on operations in Northern Ireland between 1969 and 2007 has not been formally produced to date, though the respective regimental or service histories and records are available, together with Defence's central data and the Armed Forces Memorial lists maintained by the tri-Service Joint Casualty and Compassionate Cell. The Department intends to produce a single centrally collated document in due course, however, which will be made available through gov.uk once complete.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47931/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47931/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will publish the names and causes of death of all UK service personnel who died in the course of or in connection with operations in Northern Ireland between 1969 and 2007.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","196154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47933","Department for Education","false","2014-04-28","<p>The revised statutory guidance “Careers guidance and inspiration in schools” was published on 10 April.</p><p> </p><p>Effective from September 2014, the guidance sets a clear framework for schools with a focus on preparation for work and high ambitions for every student. This important guidance will encourage schools to build links with employers to inspire and mentor pupils, helping them to develop high aspirations and realise their potential.</p><p> </p><p>Non-statutory departmental advice has also been published containing examples of schools that already offer innovative careers guidance.</p><p> </p><p>Copies of both documents have been placed in the House Library and can be found at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/careers-guidance-for-young-people-in-schools" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/careers-guidance-for-young-people-in-schools</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47933/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47933/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when he plans to publish statutory guidance on careers advice.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","196107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47934","Department for Education","false","2014-04-28","<p>The School Admissions Code does not prevent a school from becoming an all-through primary school for children aged 2 or 3 to age 11. It does, however, prevent schools from giving priority for reception places to children who have been admitted to the nursery class unless they can do so fairly and without disadvantaging children whose parents choose other forms of early education.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers are considering the Chief Schools Adjudicator's recommendation that they issue further guidance for admission authorities so that there is fair access to schools for all children.</p><p> </p><p>We take fair access very seriously but also want to explore the incentives for schools to use their expertise to enhance early years education.</p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47934/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47934/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 April 2014, Official Report, column 205W, on primary education: admissions, and of 6 March 2014, Official Report, column 904W, on academies, regarding primary school admissions from nursery schools, if he will make it his policy to reject the Chief Schools Adjudicator's recommendation to issue further guidance for admission authorities and instead amend the admissions code to enable primary schools to create all-through primary schools that include the years prior to reception.","true","Biography information for Nick Gibb","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","196101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47935","Department for Education","false","2014-04-28","<p>The Department for Education is providing funding of £918,000 to Nasen over two years to develop a special educational needs (SEN) gateway. This will provide professionals with access to free high-quality SEN resources and training materials to support children with SEN and disabilities.</p><p> </p><p>The gateway will be designed primarily for educational professionals in schools, colleges and other educational settings rather than for parents, although they will be able access the gateway. It is due to be launched in May 2014.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","196029","2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47935/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47935/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 4 March 2014, Official Report, columns 789-90, on special educational needs, when he expects the special educational needs (SEN) gateway will be available for all parents of SEN children.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","196031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47936","Department for Education","false","2014-04-28","<p>We have not yet selected the local authorities for the pilot.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47936/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47936/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2014, Official Report, column 191W, on special edcuational needs, which local authorities will trial the First-Tier Tribunal (Special Educational Needs and Disability) pilots.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","196028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47937","Department for Education","false","2014-04-28","<p>The Department for Education is providing funding of £918,000 to Nasen over two years to develop a special educational needs (SEN) gateway. This will provide professionals with access to free high-quality SEN resources and training materials to support children with SEN and disabilities.</p><p> </p><p>The gateway will be designed primarily for educational professionals in schools, colleges and other educational settings rather than for parents, although they will be able access the gateway. It is due to be launched in May 2014.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","196031","2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47937/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47937/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-04-09","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 4 March 2014, Official Report, column 789-90W, on special educational needs, what support his Department is providing to Nasen.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","196029"
